  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_276668354" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/276668354" />
    <a title="Brad" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7380358-brad"><img alt="Brad" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/276668354?book_show_action=true">Feb 12, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brad" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brad" href="/user/show/7380358-brad">Brad</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer276668354" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7158085866640398063">Jorge Amado’s novel paints a compelling portrait of a town full of characters forging a new way of life from the old social structures of the previous one. The novel begins with a bifurcated duality pitting the conservative establishment against the more liberal cultural elite, with both movements finding champions in characters that are physically and socially representative of their unique paradigms. But as the mechanism for change shifts from bullets to speeches(163), the relationship between</span>
  <span id="freeText7158085866640398063" style="display:none">Jorge Amado’s novel paints a compelling portrait of a town full of characters forging a new way of life from the old social structures of the previous one. The novel begins with a bifurcated duality pitting the conservative establishment against the more liberal cultural elite, with both movements finding champions in characters that are physically and socially representative of their unique paradigms. But as the mechanism for change shifts from bullets to speeches(163), the relationship between the two groups grows more complicated and Amado weaves profound connections between characters from both camps in such a way that belies the easy dichotomy of their differences. Driven by numerous examples of increasingly strong women who are unafraid to stand up for their beliefs, the town begins to reexamine old customs and establish new traditions that are more in keeping with the melting pot of a community that is quickly finding its own sense of self. The struggle for self-identification is paralleled in the tumultuous relationship between Gabriela and Nacib, which undoubtedly adds still more colorful life to the story’s already vivid cast. <br /><br />Through it all, Amado’s narrator maintains a light-hearted tone that pokes fun at representatives from both sides of the socioeconomic exchange. But beneath the cheerful veneer is a deeper commentary on the dangers faced by a rapidly developing community possessed of economic growth that is close to outpacing the lagging development of social services and moral responsibility that is necessary to guide wealth into productive channels of societal improvement. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="7158085866640398063" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

