    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_151446627" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/151446627" />
    <a title="Aubrey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4119460-aubrey"><img alt="Aubrey" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1472535045p2/4119460.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/151446627?book_show_action=true">Mar 01, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Aubrey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Aubrey" href="/user/show/4119460-aubrey">Aubrey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780380012053" href="/book/show/1092435.Gabriela_Clove_and_Cinnamon">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=person-of-everything">person-of-everything</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=1-read-on-hand">1-read-on-hand</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=4-star">4-star</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=r-2018">r-2018</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=r-goodreads">r-goodreads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=antidote-think-twice-all">antidote-think-twice-all</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=antidote-translated">antidote-translated</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=antidote-think-twice-read">antidote-think-twice-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=translated">translated</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer151446627" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10118959942426464744">3.5/5<br/><br/>It didn&apos;t surprise me that Amado had written political novels oriented around class struggle in his youth, for the main character of this novel is not Gabriela, however much the characters fawn over her, but the town growing into city of Ilhéus itself. Facile as Amado&apos;s characterization can get at times, the driving motivation is one of humanization of women, poor people, old people, and in some ways black people, although queer people get overly cut out of the effort. I may lower the ratin</span>
  <span id="freeText10118959942426464744" style="display:none">3.5/5<br /><br />It didn't surprise me that Amado had written political novels oriented around class struggle in his youth, for the main character of this novel is not Gabriela, however much the characters fawn over her, but the town growing into city of Ilhéus itself. Facile as Amado's characterization can get at times, the driving motivation is one of humanization of women, poor people, old people, and in some ways black people, although queer people get overly cut out of the effort. I may lower the rating later, but for now, this is a decent representative of Brazilian literature, although I find <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/22458.Machado_de_Assis" title="Machado de Assis" rel="nofollow noopener">Machado de Assis</a> and <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/836157.Hilda_Hilst" title="Hilda Hilst" rel="nofollow noopener">Hilda Hilst</a> to be much more interesting in their literary endeavors. The love story portion was gratingly boring, but the evolution and eventual triumph of justice over misogyny that underlies both introduction and conclusion was anything but, and I've had a soft spot for such ever since my first reading of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/24280.Les_Mis_rables" title="Les Misérables by Victor Hugo" rel="nofollow noopener">Les Misérables</a>. As such, I like it better than the average sprawling historical work, and I raise my hat to its socialist motivations.<br /><br />This narrative is expressive in the way certain Latin American works are, and it is nice in a sense to return to such familiar (if borderline stereotypical) writerly landscapes. Unlike others, though, this expansiveness was grounded in the potentials of civilization and the wonders humanity are capable of when banded together under a single, socially aware purpose. As I said previously, the romance was rather trite, and none of the women rise above the level of multifarious stereotype, but I appreciated the narrative emphasis on the realities of social improvement through means of enhancing infrastructure and winning on political promises that are always subsequently fulfilled. Not the most stirring to the majority of readers, but the hellscape of current politics has made me yearn for a sign of any sort of conscientiousness paid to society's marginalized. While Amado does not write out a social revolution, he does accomplish by the end of the book an eradication of at least one patriarchal justification for murder, which is often the first step in the long path towards complete and utter revitalization of an abject sector of humanity. Comforting, in a way. Almost escapist, if the writing hadn't been so lazy at times. All in all, I don't regret having <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/214836.Tent_of_Miracles" title="Tent of Miracles by Jorge Amado" rel="nofollow noopener">Tent of Miracles</a> on my shelves, and it won't be abandoned anytime soon.<br /><br />I know I'm being less stringent with this book than I usually am in my reading habits, but heightened stringency towards others has a habit of increasing the stringency I apply towards myself, and I can't afford such at the end of the semester if I don't want to risk burn out. Still, I"m in a stable enough position at the end of 2018 to not worry as much about my tight rope balancing act, and next year should as healthy an influx as what propelled this year's final moving out. I'm more assured than I was in previous years of decent grade results, and money is sufficient, if not enough to ward my continuing to go back to school. As I said, I have another Amado work, but I rarely like any author outside of a series well enough to binge upon, and Amado, sadly, is nowhere near a favorite. A healthy dose of hope in humanizing development, though? Yes, and in the future, I'll always be able to use some of that.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10118959942426464744" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


