        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer968138509" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2537512013712369140">I can appreciate the depiction of clash between the old conservative patriarchy and the progressive modernity. But I am disgusted by the depiction of women as either prim ladies of society (representing the old conservatives) or veritable sex fiends (the positive progressives). I know this was written a good while ago, and that Brazil has been more of a macho dominating culture longer than many others, but Amado&apos;s portrait of the female has not aged well. Gabriela in this story is supposed to be</span>
  <span id="freeText2537512013712369140" style="display:none">I can appreciate the depiction of clash between the old conservative patriarchy and the progressive modernity. But I am disgusted by the depiction of women as either prim ladies of society (representing the old conservatives) or veritable sex fiends (the positive progressives). I know this was written a good while ago, and that Brazil has been more of a macho dominating culture longer than many others, but Amado's portrait of the female has not aged well. Gabriela in this story is supposed to be sort of "the natural woman", behaving as women would if they weren't bound by the constraints of social conventions. But she seems more like a mentally retarded nymphomaniac to me, not being able to draw any conclusions from people's behaviour. Only Malvina comes to the conclusion that she'd be better off without a man, all other women who defies the old colonels do so by connecting to some sort of inherited promiscuity. No thoughts of letting women get involved in politics, not a word about universal suffrage, and not a hint towards that they might actually want to have a drink in a bar without being a prostitude.<br />But the environment with some vestiges of "The wild West" is very colourful, and the food and traditions are nice to read about</span>
  <a data-text-id="2537512013712369140" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


