    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_278671964" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/278671964" />
    <a title="Sajal  Shrestha" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7403184-sajal-shrestha"><img alt="Sajal  Shrestha" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1606342769p2/7403184.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/278671964?book_show_action=true">Feb 16, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sajal  Shrestha" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sajal  Shrestha" href="/user/show/7403184-sajal-shrestha">Sajal  Shrestha</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer278671964" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10458375361463510626">Gabriela, Clove and Cinnamon is a story of a city struggling to find its identity. As the city of Ileus experiences a burst of wealth due to its cacao plantations, it is caught between embracing the radical new ideas brought by migrants and holding on to its older traditions. These conflicting ideas are represented by two primary characters in the story, Colonel Ramiro and Mundhino Falcao. Colonel Ramiro, on the conservative side, is the kingmaker in the city of Ilehus and its neighboring cities</span>
  <span id="freeText10458375361463510626" style="display:none">Gabriela, Clove and Cinnamon is a story of a city struggling to find its identity. As the city of Ileus experiences a burst of wealth due to its cacao plantations, it is caught between embracing the radical new ideas brought by migrants and holding on to its older traditions. These conflicting ideas are represented by two primary characters in the story, Colonel Ramiro and Mundhino Falcao. Colonel Ramiro, on the conservative side, is the kingmaker in the city of Ilehus and its neighboring cities. After years of political maneuvering and power brokerage, Colonel Ramiro has the ultimate authority on major political decisions within the city. He rules the city with an iron fist hidden beneath a velvet glove. Mundhino, on the other hand, is an ambitious young exporter who attempts to bring both material and cultural change to the city. His charming personality and his influence wins him many new friends and admirers in iIlehus. Although on the surface it seems that both characters are fighting the battle of progress versus tradition, in a deeper level, however, it is clear that both the characters are after the same thing: power and influence, regardless of its impact on their beloved Illheus. While Mundhino is primarily fuelled by ambition to reach the same political heights as his two elder siblings, Colonel Ramiro wants to hold onto the strings that run Illheus even at the cost of economic destruction. In the middle of this all is Nacib, popularly known as the Arab. He embodies the struggle that is being played out in the city. Cacao is to Illheus what Gabriela is to Nacib, both the reasons for struggle and confusion. With the arrival of Gabriela, Nacib is also caught between the two parties whom he both calls friends. Also the personal transformation that Nacib goes through, his desires for higher status and cultural sophistication, embodies the same changes Illheus is experiencing. All in all, Jorge Amado creates a wonderful story with many beautifully developed characters and intricate plot lines that makes it almost impossible for the reader to stop reading it. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="10458375361463510626" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


