<div id="review_276625355" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/276625355" />
    <a title="Danielle" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7381388-danielle"><img alt="Danielle" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/276625355?book_show_action=true">Feb 12, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Danielle" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Danielle" href="/user/show/7381388-danielle">Danielle</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer276625355" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12508653615147130184">For those with a desire to travel through time, Jorge Amado’s Gabriela Clove, and Cinnamon offers a direct-flight to Brazil’s untamed Nordeste (the Portuguese word for the country’s northeastern region) as it was in the mid-1920s. By way of characters’ private thoughts and vivid descriptions of everyday life, readers are able to imagine exactly what is taking place in the novel, almost as if they were there observing everything firsthand. While reading, I was pleased to discover two inspirationa</span>
  <span id="freeText12508653615147130184" style="display:none">For those with a desire to travel through time, Jorge Amado’s Gabriela Clove, and Cinnamon offers a direct-flight to Brazil’s untamed Nordeste (the Portuguese word for the country’s northeastern region) as it was in the mid-1920s. By way of characters’ private thoughts and vivid descriptions of everyday life, readers are able to imagine exactly what is taking place in the novel, almost as if they were there observing everything firsthand. While reading, I was pleased to discover two inspirational young women named Gabriela and Malvina. Each faces a number of distinct challenges; however, they both exhibit strong personalities, are committed to living their distinct versions of the “good life”, and ardently refuse to conform to Ilhéus’ strict social norms. I was particularly struck by their determination and interpretations of what a woman’s life could and should in spite of the androcentric political, economic, and social climate in which live. Ultimately, Gabriela, Clove, and Cinnamon is an utterly engaging novel that successfully encapsulates Northeastern Brazil’s historically magical, steamy, unpredictable, and bitter-sweet society. <br /><br />Favorite quotes: "That's how the world is, Mr. Nacib. Everything happens when you least expect it," (Amado 33), and later Mundinho says, "I could make as much or more exporting coffee. But here I'm accomplishing something. I am somebody, you know?" (Amado 76). </span>
  <a data-text-id="12508653615147130184" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


