<div id="review_21449311" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/21449311" />
    <a title="Karen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/355071-karen"><img alt="Karen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1240016205p2/355071.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/21449311?book_show_action=true">May 02, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Karen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Karen" href="/user/show/355071-karen">Karen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780380012053" href="/book/show/1092435.Gabriela_Clove_and_Cinnamon">review of another edition</a>


          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Karen by: </span>
      My mom's estranged (former) best friend
  </div>


    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer21449311" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1981131374692335273">I wasn’t expecting to love a book in which much of the plot focuses on the dredging of a sandbar to create a direct route of cacao exportation from the Brazilian town of Ilheus. There are a lot of politics here, and as with most of the South American novels I’ve read, I often found it difficult to keep the (many) names straight, let alone the characters’ various roles in the town’s political hierarchy. <br/><br/>But this book is so joyful that the societal “issues” it may or may not be trying to address j</span>
  <span id="freeText1981131374692335273" style="display:none">I wasn’t expecting to love a book in which much of the plot focuses on the dredging of a sandbar to create a direct route of cacao exportation from the Brazilian town of Ilheus. There are a lot of politics here, and as with most of the South American novels I’ve read, I often found it difficult to keep the (many) names straight, let alone the characters’ various roles in the town’s political hierarchy. <br /><br />But this book is so joyful that the societal “issues” it may or may not be trying to address just don’t seem that important. Bad things do happen – murder, adultery and betrayal come to mind – but this book leads you to believe that all that really matters in the world is food (as long as it’s good), drink, friendship and easygoing sex. And though the increasingly strict “morals” of a developing society threaten to ruin the party, you get the feeling that they never really stand a chance. <br /><br />As an aside – inspired by the book, in which manioc meal (mashed yucca) seems to be a key player (Gabriela, a beautiful migrant who is hired as a cook, prepares it constantly for her employer/lover Nacib the Arab), I attempted to make it at home, with disastrous results. I won’t go into detail, but the smell of rotting corpse permeated the apartment for days, and I’m still finding deposits of yucca starch in unexpected places. I guess that’s why they call it fiction. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="1981131374692335273" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


