    <a title="Anna van Koeverden" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/73131686-anna-van-koeverden"><img alt="Anna van Koeverden" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1512620509p2/73131686.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2524295116?book_show_action=true">Jul 16, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Anna van Koeverden" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Anna van Koeverden" href="/user/show/73131686-anna-van-koeverden">Anna van Koeverden</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780307276650" href="/book/show/13699805-gabriela-clove-and-cinnamon">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2524295116" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13235241029245956530">I really enjoyed Amado&apos;s Dona Flor and Her Two Husbands, but this book just fell flat for me. The plot had great potential but never really carried me away. Amado did a good job of depicting life in a small sugar cane town and I did enjoy this aspect of the book but there were big chunks of the book where the story didn&apos;t advance at all. It was almost like the first 80% of the book is just an introduction and the real story happens in the last 50 or so pages. Additionally, whilst I understand th</span>
  <span id="freeText13235241029245956530" style="display:none">I really enjoyed Amado's Dona Flor and Her Two Husbands, but this book just fell flat for me. The plot had great potential but never really carried me away. Amado did a good job of depicting life in a small sugar cane town and I did enjoy this aspect of the book but there were big chunks of the book where the story didn't advance at all. It was almost like the first 80% of the book is just an introduction and the real story happens in the last 50 or so pages. Additionally, whilst I understand that the book was written and set in a different time, the portrayal of women really hasn't aged well. They're either prudish or sex crazed and all the men are obnoxious twats.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13235241029245956530" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


